**When I mean easiest solution, it is! The best solution for this problem uses recursion, and you can as close as a 0ms of runtime. However, this approach to the problem uses brute force.**

Basically, the main idea is get all the permutations and iterate them.
1.- Get the string with the number, from 1 to n.
Examples:
&emsp;n = 3
&emsp;string = "123"

&emsp;n = 5
&emsp;string = "12345"

2.- Set the counter to 1. This will help us when to stop the permutations loop.
3.- Using a while loop we will sort the permutations by ascending order.
4.- Every cycle check if our counter is equal than k, if it is return the string else increase the var.

*Documentation*
next_permutation: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/next_permutation

```
class Solution {
public:
    string getPermutation(int n, int k) {
        string permutations;
        int index = 1;

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) 
            permutations += to_string(i);

        do {
            if (index == k) return permutations;    
            else index++;
        } while (next_permutation(permutations.begin(), permutations.end()));

        return "";
    }
};
```

