***Method 1(Using hashing)***

By storing the frequency of all elements int the hashmap we can easily find which two elements are having `frequency ==1`

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
        unordered_map<int,int>mp;
        for(auto x:nums){
            mp[x]++;
        }
        vector<int>ans;
        for(auto x:mp){
            if(x.second==1){
                ans.push_back(x.first);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
***Complexity:***
```
Time: O (n)
Space: O (n)
```

***Method 2(Using bit manipulation)***
We will be needing `xor of the elements` of the complete array in two passes.

**INTUITION**
As we know the two numbers appearing once will differ at atleast `one bit `
```
Eg:- Let 1st number be 1 and 2nd be 5
1 => 0001
5 => 0101
1 and 5 differ at 3rd bit
```
So, we need to find the one bit at which numbers differ, so that we can divide the array into two groups
```
Eg :- Let array be [1,3,3,4,4,5,6,6,7,7]
We can observe that the two numbers coming once are 1 and 5, bit at which
1 and 5 differ are 3rd bit
So, number :- 1 ,3rd bit is 0 and number 5, 3rd bit is 1
```
Now we need to divide the array into two groups with numbers at `3rd bit == 0 as 1st group` and numbers with `3rd bit==1 into second`
```
Group 1 => [1,3,3]  //1 and 3 are having 3rd bit as 0
Group 2 => [4,4,5,6,6,7,7]  //4,5,6,7 are having 3rd bit as 1
```
Now xoring into respective groups will give us the two numbers.

**How to find the bit at which two numbers differ?**
We will iterate the bits of xor of complete elements (x) `(0-32)` and will check if the `ith bit of xor is one` then it is different, we will check this by the formulae:-
`x&(1<<i)`
 For those who don't know about this formulae,
 Here,
```
1 << 0 = `0000 0001`
1 << 1 = `0000 0010`
1 << 2 = `0000 0100`
``` 
and` i varies from (0-32)`
And we are using and operation for checking every bit to be one

**STEPS**
* Take xor the the complete array and store in` variable x`
* Now we need to find the bit at which the two numbers differ let it be `idx`
* The idx can be either `1 or 0`
* By dividing the set of numbers into 2 groups with first group of idx` bit==1 and second bit==0`
* Now xoring in respective groups will give us two numbers.

```
vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
        int x=0; 
        //Xoring all elements
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            x^=nums[i];
        }
        //index for bit difference
        int idx;

        //Find the bit at which two numbers differ
        for(int i=0;i<32;i++){
            if(x&(1<<i)){
                idx=i;break;
            }
        }
        //Finding the 1st number
        int first=0;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(nums[i]&(1<<idx)){
                first^=nums[i];
            }
        }
		//second number will be xor of complete and first
        int second=first^x;
        return {first,second};
    }
```
***Complexity:***
```
Time: O (n)
Space: O (1)
```

