solutions.content:
**Logic**:
Here the idea is to XOR every element in the array. As all other numbers appears exactly twice, when we XOR the entire array the resultant value will be the XOR of the numbers we need to return. Once we have the XOR, we need its operands. For this, we extract the lowest set bit in the result. If a bit is set after XOR operation, that means for the same bit position its operands might have different values. Divide the array based on this condition into two parts  and XOR both the parts separtely to find the two operands of XORed result which is our required final output.

**Example**:
Consider case of [1,2,1,3,2,5]. For this set, 
XOR of array = 6, which is XOR of 3,5.
Extracting lowest set bit and making all others zero for 6(110) gives: 2(010).
Making two sets based on XOR result gives 
Set 1 : [1,1,3]   All these elements have second lowest bit set to 0.
Set 2: [2,2,5]    All these elements have second lowest bit set to 1.



**Time Complexity:**
O(n)

**Space Complexity:**
Constant Space.

**Code**:

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
        long long int temp_res=0;
		// XOR the entire array.
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++)
            temp_res^=nums[i];

		// Extract the lowest set from the resultant value.
        int extracted_lsb=(temp_res)&(~(temp_res-1)); 
        int res_a=0, res_b=0;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(extracted_lsb&nums[i])
			    // if bit at the position is set for num[i]. XOR it to find one value.
                res_a^=nums[i];
            else
				// if bit at the position is unset for num[i]. XOR it to find another value.
                res_b^=nums[i];
        }
        vector<int> res_vec;
        res_vec.push_back(res_a);
        res_vec.push_back(res_b);
        return res_vec;

    }
};
```

