**Concept**:
**Explaination with example :**
consider a=[1,2,1,3,2,5]

**Step 1** - Finding xor of all elements (i.e atlast xor variable will be xor of only two unique elements)
			```xor=1^2^1^3^2^5 =3^5 = 6 (0110)```

**Step 2** - Then we will look for rightmost set index in xor 
			(logic is if rightmost bit on that index is 1, means one of unique element must be 1 and other must be 0 on             that same index)
			```idx=1``` (from right and 0 indexed)

**Step 3** - Now, setting bit mask by
            ```mask = 1<<idx = 0010```
			( So that, we will look for array elements that has bit==1 at that idx)

**Step 4** - Now, by taking the xorr of only elements that has bit at that idx 1...we can find 1st unique element (store in n1)

**Step 5** -  And other element will be 
```xor^n1```

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {

        int xorr{}; 
        int n1{};
        int idx{};

        for(auto& it:nums)     // calculating xor of all elements.
            xorr^=it;

        int tmp=xorr;   
        while(1)         //finding rightmost set bit idx
            if(tmp & 1)
                break;
            else{
                tmp>>=1;
                ++idx;
            }

        int mask=1<<idx;   
			for(auto& it:nums) //taking xox of elements that has bit 1 at that idx
            if(it & mask)
                n1^=it;  

         return vector<int>{xorr^n1,n1};
    }
};
```

