**Explaination-**
1. A XOR A = 0
2. So if all numbers comes even times, then the XOR of that number is 0. We'll be left with XOR of 2 numbers which appears exactly 1 time.
3. XOR of 2 numbers which not results in 0, means there are some set bits(bits with 1 value) eg. 10100 has 2 set bits.
4. Let's say number occuring only once are 7 and 8, 7 XOR 8 = 
     7 =  0111
	 8 = 1000
XOR = 1111
5. All the places where we have 1 in XOR, that means both the number have alternative bits, find the first set-bit (bit with value 1) so that if we XOR all the values again and the values which give 1 on XOR of that number put them in a different set, and rest in different set.
eg.
    XOR = 1111 
	First set-bit is at position 0, from right, put all numbers in set-1 which have 0th bit as 1, and set-2 on 0th bit as 0.
6. now if you XOR the set-1 you will get 1 unique value, and same with set-2.

