Since every number except two are repeating xor of all the numbers will give (a^b) where a and b are the distinct number. Now we just have to seperate out a and b from (a^b).

Since a and b are not repeating they are unique and will differ in atleast on bit position. We just have to find the bit position where a and b differs.
Lets just say a and b differs in i'th bit.
if we split the entire num array based on wheater i'th bit is set or not then a and b will be in two different sets.
And if we take xor of elements of first and second set seperately, you will get a and b.

Example:
[1,2,1,3,2,5]
Cumulative xor = '110'
Since 1st bit is set first bit of a and b differs.
Now we split number based on the first bit.
Set 1 : 2,2,3
Set 2 : 1,1,5

Xor Set 1 : 3
Xor Set 2 : 5

Xor will yield the unique nums as the pairs of repeating numbers will always go to the same set



```
vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
	int x = 0;
	for(auto e: nums) // cumulative xor
		x = (x^e); 

	int i = 0;
	while(((x>>i)&1) == 0){ // Finding the bit position in which the numbers differ
		i++;
	}
	int a = 0; 
	int b = 0; 
	for(auto e: nums){
		if(((e>>i)&1) == 0) // Set 1
			a = a^e;
		else
			b = b^e; // Set 2
	}
	return {a, b}; // Only a and b remains
}
```

