solutions.content:
## Basic Idea
The question states that we are given an array which has exactly two elements that occur only once, while all other elements occur exactly twice in the array. For eg : [1, 2, 4, 2, 3, 3]. Here 1 and 4 are the non repeating ones and 2 and 3 occur exactly twice. Our task is to find these two non-repeating elements of the array.

Although the question further puts constraints on the space and time complexity of the solution, but for now let us assume that only this is the question, with all relaxations allowed.

The **Naive** solution to this problem is probably not even worth mentioning, but still it just consists of choosing an element of the array, and then trying to find its second occurence. If we can, then it is not included in the answer, otherwise, it is. We stop once we get two such elements.
This is indeed a very naive solution which will cost **O(n<sup>2</sup>)** in time and **O(1)** in space.
<br>

## Optimized Solution with Extra Space (using HashMap) [Accepted]
The first thing that comes to mind whenever we talk about finding the occurence of elements in an array is a hashmap. If you have used hashmaps before, you might know that they make searching constant time (O(1)) for a space tradeoff (O(n)).
We just iterate over the array adding the elements to the hashmap, updating the number of times they occur in the array. Then we iterate over the hashmap, and include the two elements that have their occurence 1 into the result array, and then return it.
Pretty simple algorithm, but not one that the question actually wants us to follow (;D)

```
vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
	unordered_map<int, int> hashmap;
	int n = nums.size();
	for(int i = 0; i<n; i++) {
		if(hashmap.find(nums[i]) == hashmap.end()) hashmap.insert({nums[i], 0});
		hashmap[nums[i]]++;
	}
	vector<int> answer;
	int m = 0;
	for(auto i = hashmap.begin(); i!= hashmap.end(); i++) {
		if(i->second == 1) {
			//appears exactly once
			answer.push_back(i->first);
			m++;
			if(m==2) {
				break;
			}
		}
	}
	return answer;
}
```

**Time:** O(n)
**Space:** O(n)

<br>

## The Actual Question (and Solution)
Now coming to the actual constraints set by the question. We are required to solve this question in linear (O(n)) time and constant (O(1)) space!
At first, it may seem baffling to you, how could this type of occurence counting be done in O(1) space? Trust me, I felt the same way, but the problem was, we probably forgot some important information given to us on a plate by the question.

Quoting from the first line of the question "Given an integer array nums, in which exactly two elements appear only once and all the other elements appear exactly twice ...", notice the occurences of the other elements. All other elements occur exactly two times, this fact can help us eliminate all these other elements.

Looking closely, you may notice that if we take the xor of the all the elements of the array, all other elements cancel out (since a^a = 0), and we are left with just the xor of the two elements required. So, if the answer to the case was {a,b}, then the xor of the entire array will be equal to a^b.

But how would we go about finding the individual elements from their xor? 
1. We find the leftmost set bit of the xor. This bit will be 1 for one of the numbers, while 0 for the other. Let a has this bit set.
2. We iterate over the array again, this time xoring all elements that do not have this bit set.
3. At the end this xor will give us b, and the only element in the array that has this bit set would be a.
4. Then we return {a,b}

```
vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
	long long xorSum = 0;
	int n = nums.size();
	for(int i = 0; i<n; i++) {
		xorSum ^= (long long) nums[i];
	}
	//this will be equal to a ^ b where a and b are the answers;
	//finding the lowest set bit in the ans;
	//this will be in one of these two (let a)
	int lset = (int) xorSum ^ (xorSum & (xorSum - 1));
	//this will be like ..0001000.. .
	int a = 0, b= 0;
	//a will be the number with this bit set.
	//b will be the the xor of all other elements
	for(int i:nums){
		if(i & lset) {
			a ^= i;
		}
		else {
			b ^= i;
		}
	}
	return {a,b};
}
```

**Time:** O(n) as we iterate over the array twice.
**Space:** O(1) as algorithm is iterative (no recursion depth) and we only use a constant number of variables per function call.
<br>

