solutions.content:
* We need to group the single numbers with other numbers such that we form two groups, with the two single numbers in different groups. If we take the XOR of those two groups separately, we'll get the two single numbers as results (because every other element appears twice).
* To assign different groups to the single numbers, we need to find a bit in which they differ(there WILL be such a bit).
* To do that take XOR of the entire array, which will amount to the XOR of the two single numbers. We can take any set bit from this XOR (I've taken the rightmost), and it will indicate that the two single numbers have different bits at that position.
* Finally, assign all numbers with bit not set at that position to one group, and all numbers with bit set at that position to the other group. This ensures that the single numbers are in different groups.
* Take XOR of both groups separately to get the answer.

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
        int fullxor = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++)
            fullxor ^= nums[i];

        int shift = 1;

        for(int s = 1; s < 32; s++)
        {
            if((fullxor & shift) == shift)break;
            shift <<= 1;
        }

        int num1 = 0, num2 = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++)
        {
            if((nums[i] & shift) == shift) num1 ^= nums[i];
            else num2 ^= nums[i];
        }

        return vector<int>{num1, num2};
    }
};
```

