solutions.content:
* Suppose X and Y are 2 numbers that appear once and all other numbers appear twice.
* If we `XOR` all the array's elements, the value would be actually `X XOR Y`. This value will be surely not zero since X and Y are different.
* We will pick up any bit that is 1 in `X XOR Y`, name it `mask` for example.
* suppose X has bit 0 at mask's position and Y has bit 1 at mask's position.
* here we divide all elements into 2 types. One has bit 0 at mask's position, the other has bit 1 at mask's position. we can be sure that all duplicate elements can be in the same pile.
* we walk through the array again, the first `XOR` result will be equal to X and the second `XOR` result will be equal to Y

