solutions.content:
#### All we need to implement LFU cache is **2 hash maps**, **1 doubly linked list** and **1 integer variable**.
<br/>

 **Two hash maps and a variable will function as follows:**
_______________________________________________________
<br/>

1) **freqMap** : hashmap<  **freq**,  **list< (key,value) >**  > 

For each frequency (of key-value pairs in LFU cache) this hashmap will store doubly linked list of key-value pairs corresponding to that freq.

	E.g. Doubly linked list of (key,value) with frequency of 1 and 2:

	freqMap[1] = (1,2) -> (3,6) -> (1,8) -> null
	freqMap[2] = (2,2) -> (9,4) -> (7,8) -> null


2) **keyMap** : unordered_map<  **key**,  **pair< freq, list< (key,value) >::iterator>**  > keyMap;

For each key in the LFU cache this hashmap will map it to the location where the key is present in **freqMap** by storing both frequency (for finding the exact linked list in which the key-value is present) and iterator ( for locating key-value in the corresponding list in O(1) time ).

3) **lowestFreq**: int

We also need a variable to store the lowest frequency with each key-value is present in LFU cache.

<br/>


**put() and get() methods will work as follows:**
____________________________________________________
<br/>

1) **put(key, value)**:

We will be calling **put()** method in two possible scenarios.

**Scenario 1**: We want to add a new (not already present) key-value pair into the LFU cache. Corresponding to this scenario we have to handle two cases:

_Case 1_: **LFU cache is not full.**

For this case first we will add the key-value pair to the list with frequency 1 (in **freqMap[1]**). Then we will also add this key to **keyMap** along with its frequency and location in its list. 
Now, we must also update **lowestFreq** to be equal to 1.

_Case 2_: **LFU cache is full.**

If the LFU cache is full then we must first fetch the first key-value pair from the beginning of the list (beginning because we want to remove the least recently used key) with lowest frequency. 
After getting the key-value pair we must remove the the key-value pair from its list and also we must remove the key from **keyMap**. 
Now we have made space for putting new key-value pair into the LFU cache. All we need to do now is call **put()** method with key-value to be added and _Case 1_ will handle it.

**Scenario 2**: We want to update the value of an already present key in the LFU Cache.

For this first we need to find out what is the frequency **freq** of the key-value pair and the location **it** of this key-value pair in **freqMap**. 

If the **freq** is equal to the **lowestFreq** and the current key-value pair is the only one in its linked list then it is neccessary that we increment the **lowestFreq** by 1, otherwise we can leave it as it is.

Now using **freq** (to get the corresponding list from **freqMap**) and **it** ( to locate key-value in the list in O(1) ) we can remove the key-value pair from its current list and add it to the list associated with frequency **freq+1** in **freqMap**, then we will also update **keyMap** with new frequency and location of key-value pair.

```cpp
void put(int key, int value) {

	// Scenario 1:
	if (!keyMap.count(key)) {
		if (keyMap.size() < cap) {  // Case 1:
			freqMap[1].emplace_back(key, value);
			keyMap[key] = {1, --freqMap[1].end()};
			lowestFreq = 1;
		} else {  // Case 2:
			if (lowestFreq == 0) return;
			auto [k, v] = freqMap[lowestFreq].front();
			freqMap[lowestFreq].erase(freqMap[lowestFreq].begin());
			keyMap.erase(k);
			put(key, value);
		}
		return;
	} 
 // Scenario 2:
  if (keyMap.count(key)) {
		auto [freq, it] = keyMap[key];
		if (freqMap[freq].size() == 1 and freq == lowestFreq) lowestFreq++;
		freqMap[freq].erase(it);
		freqMap[freq+1].emplace_back(key, value);
		keyMap[key] = {freq, --freqMap[freq+1].end()};
	}
}
```

2) **get(key)**:

First we will check for presence of key in **keyMap**. 

_Case 1_: **If key is not present.** We must return -1 in this case.

_Case 2_: **If key is present.** We will store, in a variable **val**, the value associated with the key. And then to update the key-value pair's frequency we will call **put(key,val)** method.

```cpp
int get(int key) {
	if(mp.count(key)){
		int val = ( *(mp[key].second) ).second;
		put(key,val);
		return val;
	}
	return -1;
}
```


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**Full Code:**

```
class LFUCache {

    unordered_map<int, list<pair<int, int>>> freqMap;
    unordered_map<int, pair<int, list<pair<int, int>>::iterator>> keyMap;
    int lowestFreq = 0;
    int cap;

    public:
    LFUCache(int capacity) {
        cap = capacity;
    }

    int get(int key) {
        if (keyMap.count(key)) {
            int val = (*(keyMap[key].second)).second;
            put(key, val);
            return val;
        }
        return -1;
    }

    void put(int key, int value) {
        if (!keyMap.count(key)) {
            if (keyMap.size() < cap) {
                freqMap[1].emplace_back(key, value);
                keyMap[key] = {1, --freqMap[1].end()};
                lowestFreq = 1;
            } else {
                if (lowestFreq == 0) return;
                auto [k, v] = freqMap[lowestFreq].front();
                freqMap[lowestFreq].erase(freqMap[lowestFreq].begin());
                keyMap.erase(k);
                put(key, value);
            }
        } else {
            auto [freq, it] = keyMap[key];
            if (freqMap[freq].size() == 1 and freq == lowestFreq) lowestFreq++;
            freqMap[freq].erase(it);
            freqMap[freq+1].emplace_back(key, value);
            keyMap[key] = {freq+1, --freqMap[freq+1].end()};
        }
    }
};
```

