# Code
```
class LFUCache {
public:

    // Data Structure Requirements

    // 1. Data structure to store key and value and also how many times that key is used in get
    // function. 

    // 2. For same frequency, we need to remove the key that occured first.
    // So, we need the order of key inputs

    // 3. We need to remove the least frequently used - LFU. So, we need the minimum
    // frequency of elements that exist currently in our data structure (cache)

    // For Step 1, => simple unordered_map, as we need key, value and frequency too.
    // So, unordered_map with pair => unordered_map<int, pair<int, int>> m; {key : {value, freq}}
    // Time taken => O(1), queurying an unordered_map to see if a key exists or not in get function

    // To do step 2, we need a data structure that maintains order of input
    // Options - array, vector, stack, queue, linked list
    // Not options - map, set, unordered_map, unordered_set, tree, graph

    // To do step 3 i.e., need to find min_freq =>
    // We can do it O(n) by traversing the built map in Step 1.
    // But to do it in O(1) time, we need to store all keys in the form of frequency buckets such as
    // All keys having frequency 1 are in one bucket / container, 
    // all keys having frequency 2 are in an other bucket / contrainer, similarily for 3 and so on.
    // If a bucket doesn't have any value, we remove that bucket.

    // To make a bucket / container pair to each frequency we need a map, 
    // and we will store min_freq in a seperate varaible for instantly getting to the mapped container
    // with the min_freq in the built map.
    // Since the order of frequencies don't matter, as we need only min_freq and we have it in another
    // variable, so we will use an unordered_map => {freq : {container}}

    // Now, if we have multiple keys with same frequency, they will all be in one container
    // So, we need to differentiate them using order in which they arrived. We need to maintain order
    // Now, possible options from step 2 are =>
    // array, vector, stack, queue, linked list
    // Array - No. Why? Because we don't know how many elements will come, and if we take maximum
    // no of elements say 2*10^5 [from question constraint]
    // Removing one element that came first will take O(n) time. which will be too slow. 
    // We need O(1).
    // Similar is the case with vector, maintains order but removal O(n)
    // Stack & Queue, they can remove in O(1) but only at top and fromt. 
    // they can't access elements in middle and remove them. 
    // But Why we need to access the elements in middle somewhere?
    // Because, when we will be updating the frequency of a key, we need to remove it from
    // the previous bucket / container and add it to the new frequency bucket / container
    // Here, we don't know where the key is present in the previous bucket / container.
    // which raises another requirement => 

    // 4. Need to store the location of keys in frequency buckets.
    // So, the only option we have is the linked list or list<int> in c++ 
    // list<int> is internally implements as a double linked list.
    // Now, why list<int> ? Because it is the only option ? NO.
    // Because it fulfills all our requirements.
    // It will store keys in order in which they appear.
    // We can store iterators to the location of keys in an unordered_map. Why unordereder map?
    // Because order of keys don't matter. Their location will let us know their order.
    // So, we will store keys with their iterators in a unordered_map => {key : iterator of list}
    // So that we can remove them from previous frequency buckets in O(1) time
    // And add keys to new frequency buckets in O(1) time.
    // Updating their iterators in O(1) time as well.
    // 
    // So also need two variables to globally access, total capacity and current capacity.
    // So we don't outrun the cache memory.

    // So after looking at all requirements and analysis.
    // We need 3 maps and 3 variables.

    // Map 1 => unordered. Structure => {key : {value, freq}}
    // fulfills requirement 1, randon key check in get function

    // Map 2 => unordered. Structure => {key : list<int>}
    // fulfills requirement 2 & 3, order of keys stored with their frequency buckets 

    // Map 3 => unordered. Structure => {key : list<int> :: iterator}
    // fulfills requirement 4, randomly accessing positions of keys in frequency buckets

    // Variable 1 => int. curr_size => stores current size of cache
    // Variable 2 => int. total_cap => stores total capacity of cache and accessible to all member functions
    // Variable 3 => int. min_freq => stores the current min_freq in the LFU.


    unordered_map<int, pair<int, int>> avl_keys;
    unordered_map<int, list<int>> freq_bucket;
    unordered_map<int, list<int>::iterator> key_pos;

    int curr_size = 0, total_cap = 0, min_freq = 0;

    LFUCache(int capacity) {
        curr_size = 0;
        total_cap = capacity;
    }

    int get(int key) {

        // Checking if the given key exists in our cacke of avl_keys
        if (avl_keys.find(key) == avl_keys.end()) 
            return -1;

        // Getting current frequecy
        int curr_freq = avl_keys[key].second;

        // Removing key from previous frequency bucket using the key's iterator from key_pos
        freq_bucket[curr_freq].erase(key_pos[key]);

        // Increasing frequency
        avl_keys[key].second += 1;

        int new_freq = avl_keys[key].second;

        // Adding key to new frequency bucket
        freq_bucket[new_freq].push_back(key);

        // Updating the key's iterator to the end of new frequency bucket
        key_pos[key] = --freq_bucket[new_freq].end();
        // Any thoughts on why doing -- before the end iterator. 
        // If you don't know, you will get the answer at the end of the post.

        // Suppose if the current key was having the minimum frequency, 
        // We have removed it from the minimum frequency bucket
        // So, we need to update the minimum frequency

        // Checking if the currrent list of min_freq is empty or not, if yes increasing min_freq by 1
        if (freq_bucket[min_freq].empty())
            min_freq += 1;

        // returning the value paired to the current key
        return avl_keys[key].first;

    }

    void put(int key, int value) {

        // If capacity is 0, simply return
        if (total_cap == 0) return;

        // If the key is present in avl_keys, update its value through get function
        // Why? Why not simply access current avl_keys map and update the value.
        // Because if we simply access current avl_keys map and update the value 
        // it will not reflect that this key has been used, and its value is updated.
        // So, call get() function, if the key is present, service the current key and then
        // update its value to the new value passed to the function
        int prev_value = get(key);

        // If key is present -1 will not be returned according to the definition of get function
        if (prev_value != -1) 
        {
            // update to the new value
            avl_keys[key].first = value;

            // return, as there is nothing else to do, and size of the cache is not increased 
            return;
        }

        // If the cache size is filled up to the top, remove the least frequent - least recent key
        if (curr_size >= total_cap)
        {
            // Get the first key in min_freq bucket. Why first? Because if came the earliest - least recent
            int lr_key = freq_bucket[min_freq].front();   // lr_key = least recent key

            // Remove lr_key from avl_keys
            avl_keys.erase(lr_key);

            // Remove the lr_key from key_pos
            key_pos.erase(lr_key);

            // Remove lr_key from frequeny bucket as well
            freq_bucket[min_freq].pop_front();

            // Decrease curr_size
            curr_size -= 1;

        }

        // Adding new key and its value
        avl_keys[key] = {value, 1};

        // Updating min_freq
        min_freq = 1;

        // Adding it in frequency bucket 
        freq_bucket[min_freq].push_back(key);

        // Adding new key's iterator to the end of min_freq i.e. 1, as the new key arrived just now
        key_pos[key] = --freq_bucket[min_freq].end();
        // Again saw -- before the end iterator. You are about to have the answer.

        // Increasing curr_size by 1 as new key added
        curr_size += 1;

    }
};

// /**
//  * Your LFUCache object will be instantiated and called as such:
//  * LFUCache* obj = new LFUCache(capacity);
//  * int param_1 = obj->get(key);
//  * obj->put(key,value);
//  */


// Why am I doing -- before updating the end iterator for every key.
// This '--' is called decrementing the iterator, i.e., moving iterator back by 1.
// The freq_bucket[min_freq].end() or end(freq_bucket[min_freq]) returns an iterator to the 
// end of the freq_bucket[min_freq] container or current container. 
// In simple words, it points to the next memory location after the end element of the container

// Now, as our key is last(end) element but certainly inside the container, not outside the container. 
// Using end() iterator we move to the next location after the last element, which is outside container and then we move back by 1 place to get the iterator of the last element that is inside the container and pointing to the last element.
// That's why I'm decrementing the end iterator before assigning it to the last key.

// Mathematically, for every container we have two pointers begin and end 
// which holds values like this in range. [begin, end)
// Notice, the closing brackets of end, it doesn't include the end iterator.

// You can draw a similar analogy to indexing in arrays.
// For int arr[N]. Indexing holds [0, N) i.e. from 0 to N-1. not N.

// If you still didn't understand you can refer the following post for list<int> iterators.
// https://cplusplus.com/reference/list/list/
```

